302","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1252–Female":"1252–Deceased","1252":"1252","14 May 1329":"14 May 1329","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1300":"about 1300","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England":"Shirburn, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","West Firle, Sussex, England":"West Firle, Sussex, England","Southampton, Hampshire,, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"St","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Claire","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Klaric","meanings":["Croatian (<b>Klarić</b>) and Slovenian (<b>Klarič</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Klara</i> (see   Claire  )."]},{"name":"Clare","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":45,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":58,"year":"1328","julianDay":220